      Web3 economics
   =20
 =20
Here=E2=80=99s a trade.=09You start a business. Let=E2=80=99s say it=E2=80=
=99s a platform business, where you connect buyers and sellers of something=
.[1] You connect people who want to rent out their cars or their houses and=
 people who want to use them, or you run an exchange to connect buyers and =
sellers of stock or art or Beanie Babies.=C2=A0=09Your platform charges a f=
ee. Say you charge 2% of the value of each transaction for yourself.=C2=A0=
=09You start doing some transactions with yourself. You list your house on =
the platform and then rent it from yourself, you sell some Beanie Babies to=
 yourself, whatever. You set up different accounts under different names (o=
r enlist your friends) to conceal this. You charge yourself a fee; you do $=
1,000 worth of transactions and pay yourself $20. Your net cost here is pre=
tty much zero, since you=E2=80=99re just sending money to yourself, though =
there may be some frictional costs.[2]=09The next month, you do it again, b=
ut more so. You do $2,000 of transactions with yourself and pay yourself $4=
0.=09The next month, you go to a venture capitalist. =E2=80=9CLook at this =
business,=E2=80=9D you say. =E2=80=9CWe are doing gross transactions of $2,=
000 a month, our revenue is $40 a month, we are already profitable and we=
=E2=80=99re growing at 100% per month.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=09The venture capital=
ist is like =E2=80=9Cooh this business looks amazing, I=C2=A0love a fast-gr=
owing platform business, I will invest at 20x revenue.=E2=80=9D By =E2=80=
=9Crevenue=E2=80=9D she means $480 a year (your current annualized run rate=
) so she values your business at $9,600. She buys 10% of your company for $=
960.=09You stop trading with yourself, the platform=E2=80=99s revenue goes =
to zero, the venture capitalist is out $960 and you keep the money. A year =
later you run this trade again with a different business and a different, o=
r the same, venture capitalist. =E2=80=9CI have learned so much from my fai=
led startup,=E2=80=9D you tell VCs.=09Or! Even better! You put out a press =
release saying =E2=80=9CProminent Venture Capitalist Invests In Awesome Fas=
t-Growing Platform,=E2=80=9D you get a lot of attention, and people start t=
rading on your platform for real. You start to get real revenue, you become=
 a real business, you stop trading with yourself, revenue keeps going up, a=
nd you and the venture capitalist both become rich.The main point of this t=
rade is that, in a frothy market for fast-growing companies, you can sell $=
1 of the right kind of revenue for much more than $1, and so it is worth yo=
ur while to=C2=A0create=C2=A0some revenue, dress it up to=C2=A0look like th=
e right kind of revenue and then sell it to someone.But another=C2=A0point =
of this trade (the one in Step=C2=A08) is that in network-effects businesse=
s these things can be self-fulfilling, and a fake business can turn into a =
real one.[3] If someone is looking to rent a house in an app, she=E2=80=99s=
 going to go to the app she=E2=80=99s heard of; if yours is getting a lot o=
f press for growing quickly and raising lots of money, she=E2=80=99ll go to=
 your app.=C2=A0This trade, as I described it, is basically fraud,[4] and s=
ometimes people do it and  get in trouble for it. But there are subtler and=
 far more interesting versions of the trade. Here is a very important one; =
let=E2=80=99s call it the =E2=80=9CWeb2 version=E2=80=9D:=09You start a pla=
tform business.=09You charge a fee of $2 per transaction.=09You go to ventu=
re capitalists and raise some money.=09You use the money to pay people, say=
, $3 per transaction to use your service. You pay them $3 per transaction a=
nd they pay you back $2 in fees. They keep $1. Free money!=09You get a lot =
of users, because everyone wants to use a service that pays them to use it.=
=09Now you have the good things: Lots of (real) users, lots of revenue, fas=
t growth.=09You do have one bad thing, which is that you lose money on ever=
y transaction.=09That=E2=80=99s fine! =E2=80=9CCustomer acquisition costs a=
re high right now,=E2=80=9D you (and your investors!) say, =E2=80=9Cbut the=
y will come down as the platform matures and achieves scale.=E2=80=9D=09You=
 go to some more venture capitalists and raise a=C2=A0ton=C2=A0of money on =
that premise. Or you go public on that premise.=C2=A0=09You stop paying peo=
ple to use the service.=09Maybe Step 8 was right! Maybe by this time your u=
sers=C2=A0are so dependent on the service, and the service is so good, and =
the network effects are so powerful, that they keep using it once you start=
 charging them to use it instead of paying them to use it. And then your se=
rvice is a huge success and you=E2=80=99re a billionaire.=09Or maybe it was=
 wrong, the service dies, the venture capitalists lose their investment and=
 you get to keep whatever cash you took out and do this again in a year as =
a battle-hardened=C2=A0repeat founder.The Web2 version of the trade is cent=
ral to the story of the last decade in the U.S. tech industry. We sometimes=
 called it the =E2=80=9CMoviePass economy,=E2=80=9D the idea that venture c=
apitalists would subsidize consumers=E2=80=99 lifestyles because they value=
d customer growth=C2=A0above everything else (including profitability). Or =
there=E2=80=99s the term =E2=80=9Cblitzscaling,=E2=80=9D the idea that by t=
hrowing enormous quantities of money at a company in a network-effects busi=
ness you can make it the dominant player and then pivot to profitability.=
=C2=A0There is no single outcome to these stories, no simple lesson to take=
 from them. Sometimes it=E2=80=99s the outcome in Step 11 above: User acqui=
sition costs decline with scale and network effects, you jack up the price,=
 and the unprofitable fast-growing subsidized service becomes profitable. O=
ther times it=E2=80=99s the outcome in Step 12. MoviePass  went hilariously=
 bankrupt.=C2=A0One way to characterize the Web2 version is that instead of=
=C2=A0trading with yourself, you=C2=A0got your investors to trade with you.=
 You generated volume on your platform=C2=A0from your investors, indirectly=
, by taking their money (the investment in Step 3) and turning it into reve=
nue (the customer subsidy in Step 4). A dollar of investment=C2=A0capital c=
an be turned into revenue, and then sold to new investors at a multiple of =
that revenue. This is arguably=C2=A0good=C2=A0for your (early) investors. T=
hey=C2=A0want=C2=A0a higher valuation. They are happy for you to turn their=
 money into revenue. They hope that you will turn it into long-term stable =
recurring revenue (Step 11). But if you just turn it into fake revenue, the=
n maybe they can still sell their shares to the next sucker before it colla=
pses.We talked last month about the economics of Web3, the popular current =
term for crypto platform businesses.  I wrote:A basic premise of Web3 is th=
at every product is simultaneously an investment opportunity. If you sign u=
p for a Web3 social network or chat room or trading venue or let=E2=80=99s-=
buy-the-Constitution lark, you will get some of that project=E2=80=99s toke=
ns, which will entitle you to use the project=E2=80=99s app or exchange or =
Constitution, and which will give you some notional say in the decentralize=
d governance of the project. Also the tokens will appreciate in value if th=
e project takes off and more people want to use it. It=E2=80=99s as if bein=
g an early user of Facebook or Uber also automatically made you a sharehold=
er of Facebook or Uber, and when those services got huge you got rich.The m=
ove is to combine (1) Web3 economics (every product is an investment) with =
(2) the basic=C2=A0trade I have sketched out here (turn investment capital =
into revenue). Here is how that move might work:=09You start a platform bus=
iness on Web3, crypto, blockchains, etc. It has a =E2=80=9Cgovernance token=
,=E2=80=9D which is a little bit like a share of stock but you get to say i=
t=E2=80=99s not a security.=09You charge a fee of 2% for people who use the=
 platform. Holders of the governance token might have some undefined, it=E2=
=80=99s-definitely-not-a-security future economic right to those fees.=C2=
=A0=09You give people governance tokens for using your platform. These are =
rewards to incentivize early adopters, and they decline over time on an exp=
licit schedule: People who use the platform a lot on the first week get a l=
ot of governance tokens, people who use it a lot the second week get fewer,=
 people who use it in the sixth month get even fewer, etc.=09There is an ex=
change of money for tokens, but indirectly. People use your platform, they =
pay you (in dollars, Ether, etc.) to use the platform, and you pay them (in=
 governance tokens) for using the platform. Also, though, they get to do wh=
atever it is they do on the platform. In theory this could be renting out h=
ouses or cars or whatever, though in practice most crypto platform business=
es are about trading crypto. Let=E2=80=99s say your business is an exchange=
 for trading non-fungible tokens. People trade NFTs on your platform, they =
pay you a fee for each trade, and (early on) you give them governance token=
s for each trade.=09So each early user of the platform is also an investor,=
 and the more they use it the more they are investing.=09They can sell the =
governance tokens freely because all of this stuff is effectively unregulat=
ed.=09How much are the governance tokens worth? It is hard to say, but they=
 are sort of like shares of stock. Their value is some increasing function =
of the expected future fee revenues of your platform, plus they have some i=
ntangible meme-y value based on how much hype your platform is getting.=09T=
he more trading there is on your platform, the more fees you collect and th=
e more successful your business looks, and the more your governance token i=
s worth, both because its expected cash flows are higher and because it get=
s more hype and attention.=09So people rush to your platform to trade as mu=
ch as possible, which pumps up the value of the governance token, and they =
cheerfully pay=C2=A0you the 2% fee to get governance tokens that they can s=
ell at an immediate profit.=09These people do not necessarily want the NFTs=
 that are being sold on your platform, so=C2=A0they=C2=A0trade with themsel=
ves. They set up two crypto wallets and sell NFTs from one to the other, cr=
eating fake volume, =E2=80=9Cwash trades.=E2=80=9D The trades aren=E2=80=99=
t real, the trades are just (1) an excuse to pay you a 2% fee on a large no=
tional in exchange for a lot of valuable governance tokens and (2) a way to=
 make your platform look popular so that the governance tokens become valua=
ble and they can sell them at a profit.=09And people buy the governance tok=
ens because (1) your platform is popular, (2) it is growing fast,=C2=A0(3) =
it is making money, and (4) it is getting a lot of hype =E2=80=94=C2=A0exac=
tly the reasons a venture capitalist would have invested in your platform i=
n the Web2 version.=09Eventually you stop handing out so many governance to=
kens=C2=A0(the rewards decline on a set schedule, see Step 3), and people s=
top doing huge wash trades with themselves to build hype and collect govern=
ance tokens.=09Maybe then your thing collapses, the early wash traders made=
 a fortune, and the people who bought their governance tokens are holding t=
he bag.=09Or maybe not! Maybe all the fake trading created enough hype for =
your platform to attract real trading, and your platform becomes good and p=
eople keep using it even after you stop paying them to use it.The Web3 vers=
ion effectively combines the user incentives and the venture capitalist inc=
entives from the Web2 version. Whereas the Web2 version of this trade=C2=A0=
indirectly=C2=A0takes money from venture capitalists and turns it into reve=
nue, so that you can sell more shares to venture capitalists at a high mult=
iple of revenue, the Web3 version=C2=A0directly=C2=A0takes money from user-=
investors and turns it into revenue, so that you (and they) can sell more g=
overnance tokens to more user-investors at an even higher Web3-hype-driven =
multiple of revenue.=C2=A0Web3 has refined and perfected this trade,=C2=A0i=
n a way that makes it just about plausibly sustainable.=E2=80=9CThis is, es=
sentially, a pyramid scheme,=E2=80=9D said Dror Poleg in an infamous post a=
bout Web3 that  I quoted the last time we discussed this.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CA P=
onzi. But it makes sense. It will be the dominant marketing method of the n=
ext decade and beyond.=E2=80=9D I don=E2=80=99t like it! But I am=C2=A0not =
confident that he=E2=80=99s wrong.Anyway here=E2=80=99s a story from last w=
eek from Andrew Hayward at Decrypt:The NFT market got a jolt this week when=
 surprise new entrant LooksRare started piling up massive Ethereum trading =
volume numbers. But as trading rises on the OpenSea rival, it has become cl=
ear that some traders are manipulating LooksRare=E2=80=99s token-based rewa=
rds system via a form of wash trading=E2=80=94and the platform doesn=E2=80=
=99t appear to mind.LooksRare is built around the LOOKS token, which the pl=
atform is airdropping to 185,000 wallets of eligible OpenSea users to try a=
nd lure them over to the platform. The platform also pays out its daily ama=
ssed transaction fees to all users who stake the LOOKS token in the form of=
 Wrapped Ethereum (WETH).On top of that, LooksRare also has a stash of LOOK=
S tokens that it will distribute daily to users who trade NFTs in select, v=
erified collections=E2=80=94including the Bored Ape Yacht Club and Doodles.=
 At a current price of $4.23 per token, the marketplace is giving away more=
 than $12.1 million worth of LOOKS tokens each day, although the tally will=
 shrink over the course of the next year.For now, however, some traders app=
ear eager to manipulate the rewards model. Over the course of the last day,=
 LooksRare has seen numerous NFT trades that go back and forth between the =
same two wallets, including a Meebits NFT that sold for about $50 million w=
orth of WETH each time. That=E2=80=99s $100 million worth of trading volume=
 in two transactions.Dozens of other Loot and Meebits NFTs have sold for ab=
out $3 million worth of WETH apiece in numerous back-and-forth transactions=
, as seen on the top NFT sales list at CryptoSlam. By contrast, the average=
 sale price of a Meebits NFT on leading marketplace OpenSea over the last w=
eek was about 4.1 ETH ($13,800 at today=E2=80=99s value), while Loot NFTs s=
old for an average of under 2.2 ETH ($7,400) each.It=E2=80=99s a form of wa=
sh trading=E2=80=94that is, manipulating the market by making it look like =
there=E2=80=99s more activity than there would be organically. Wash trading=
 can be used to boost demand for a financial asset or to hide ill-gotten ga=
ins from illicit activities, for example. Critics often accuse the NFT mark=
et of harboring widespread wash trading and money laundering.In this case, =
the wash trading is apparently being done to significantly boost the potent=
ial share of trading rewards that users receive for buying and selling NFTs=
 on the site. Traders still have to pay the 2% transaction fee, as well as =
standard Ethereum gas fees (network transaction costs), but Meebits and Loo=
t are both collections that do not charge creator royalties on top of those=
 fees.In other words, traders aiming to manipulate LooksRare=E2=80=99s rewa=
rds system are betting that the rewards they receive in LOOKS tokens and WE=
TH will be more valuable than the LooksRare transaction fees and Ethereum g=
as fees they=E2=80=99re spending in the process.And here is a related=C2=A0=
Twitter thread.=C2=A0The Web3 version of the trade will probably be=C2=A0ce=
ntral to the story of the next decade in the=C2=A0tech industry, so that=E2=
=80=99ll be fun I guess.
