0 of taxable income? That seems inconvenient! Here=E2=80=99s a  Bloomberg N=
ews story from last week:Investors and creators of nonfungible tokens -- a =
market that has ballooned to $44 billion, Chainalysis data show, and attrac=
ted fans from Justin Bieber to Melania Trump -- face billions of dollars in=
 taxes and rates as high as 37%, according to tax experts. Internal Revenue=
 Service officials who deal with tax evaders say they are gearing up for a =
crackdown.=C2=A0The surprises looming for NFT enthusiasts when tax filing s=
eason begins this month are crypto=E2=80=99s latest wake-up call from Washi=
ngton as officials across the U.S. government set their sights on the burge=
oning industry. The rules about taxing tokens aren=E2=80=99t clear, leaving=
 NFT collectors scrambling to calculate how much they owe. Investors may no=
t realize they need to pay any taxes at all or that they should file more t=
han once a year, increasing the odds they=E2=80=99ll face future penalties.=
By like 2040 the entire U.S. government will be funded by taxing NFT wash t=
raders.Incidentally! There are a lot of people in the world and almost all =
of them would prefer to pay lower taxes rather than higher taxes. But there=
 is a small category of people who are intensely interested in paying highe=
r taxes. There are people who will walk into a casino with a sack of cash, =
buy $1 million of chips at a table, carry them directly to a cashier, cash =
the chips out for $1 million, declare $1 million of gambling income to the =
IRS and pay taxes on it.[5]=C2=A0Of course they don=E2=80=99t have $1 milli=
on of gambling income in this scenario: They walked in with $1 million and =
walked out with $1 million, their gambling income is zero.=C2=A0Why call it=
 gambling income? Because once you declare $1 million of gambling income an=
d pay taxes on it, you can use what=E2=80=99s left over=C2=A0to buy houses =
and cars and college tuition and stuff. Whereas=C2=A0before=C2=A0they decla=
red it as gambling income, when it was just cash in a sack, it was =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0probably it was the proceeds of selling illegal drugs, though ther=
e are other ways to end up with $1 million of questionable cash in a sack. =
If you buy a house with=C2=A0cash in a sack it is going to raise questions.=
This is called =E2=80=9Cmoney laundering,=E2=80=9D and the essential compon=
ent of money laundering is=C2=A0generating fake taxable income. If you take=
 $13,800 out of=C2=A0your (legitimate, previously taxed) bank account, and =
