Yesterday Microsoft Corp. announced that it will buy Activision Blizzard In=
c. for about $69 billion, a price that reflects more or less:=09The value o=
f Activision=E2=80=99s business to public shareholders,=C2=A0plus=09A contr=
ol premium that Microsoft is paying to acquire the whole thing, plus=09Some=
 share of the synergies Microsoft can get from, like, saying the word =E2=
=80=9Cmetaverse=E2=80=9D a lot on conference calls,=C2=A0minus=09The expect=
ed value of government and private lawsuits and other risks having to do wi=
th a sexual misconduct scandal at Activision.I am not going to attempt to q=
uantify any of those elements except that=C2=A0Activision was trading at ab=
out $90 to $99=C2=A0per share last summer,=C2=A0before the allegations came=
 out, and it closed last week (before the merger news) at $65.39. Roughly $=
20 billion of market capitalization went away due, at least in part, to Act=
ivision=E2=80=99s sexual misconduct scandal. Microsoft will pay $95 per sha=
re, a substantial premium to Activision=E2=80=99s recent price, but below w=
here it was trading last June.=C2=A0And the consensus is that Microsoft saw=
 an opportunity to buy Activision=C2=A0specifically=C2=A0because its scanda=
ls depressed its stock price. =E2=80=9CActivision Blizzard=E2=80=99s Workpl=
ace Problems Spurred $75 Billion Microsoft Deal=E2=80=9D is the Wall Street=
 Journal=E2=80=99s headline; =E2=80=9C Activision Sexual Misconduct Fallout=
 Prompted Microsoft to Pursue Deal=E2=80=9D is Bloomberg=E2=80=99s. And Act=
ivision=E2=80=99s board, faced with a scandal that was a potentially existe=
ntial risk, decided to cut off that risk by cashing out. =E2=80=9CSome dire=
ctors didn=E2=80=99t believe shareholders and employees would be comfortabl=
e without a major change but weren=E2=80=99t willing to try to oust Mr. Kot=
ick,=E2=80=9D reports the Journal, and either option =E2=80=94=C2=A0firing =
the CEO or keeping him =E2=80=94=C2=A0had serious risks. Ninety-five dollar=
s in cash has much less risk.A couple of points here. One is that, for Micr=
osoft, Activision=E2=80=99s scandals represent a source of synergy. Right n=
ow the value of Activision is reduced because there is controversy about it=
s chief executive officer=E2=80=99s=C2=A0involvement in the scandal, a cont=
roversy that has drawn lawsuits and regulatory action and might cost Activi=
sion customers and relationships. But when the deal closes, Activision will=
 be run by Microsoft, whose CEO is not connected to this scandal and is not=
 especially=C2=A0scandalous in general. (It seems like the plan is for Acti=
vision=E2=80=99s current, scandalous CEO to depart when the deal closes, th=
ough that is not entirely clear.) Activision will go from being a company r=
un by a scandal-plagued CEO, which is bad, to being a division of Microsoft=
, which is neutral. This is an improvement! Microsoft will=C2=A0add value=
=C2=A0to Activision by being boring.=C2=A0Some number of valuable relations=
hips that independent Activision would have lost will be preserved by Micro=
soft-Activision. Ben Thompson writes:Microsoft does, of course, inherit the=
 lawsuit and associated issues that led to this decline, but that almost se=
ems like an opportunity in its own right: whereas acquisitions usually pres=
ent concerns about integrating different cultures and management teams =E2=
=80=94 after all, you don=E2=80=99t want to destroy whatever it is you boug=
ht =E2=80=94 Microsoft actually has full license to completely wipe out Act=
ivision Blizzard=E2=80=99s management team and culture and instill its own =
way of doing things.Second, I write a lot around here about the idea that =
=E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud.=E2=80=9D Anything bad that happens=
 at a public company can become the basis for a securities-fraud lawsuit al=
leging that the company deceived investors about the bad thing and they los=
t money when the stock dropped. And of course Activision=E2=80=99s stock dr=
opped=C2=A0and there are=C2=A0a bunch of securities-fraud lawsuits=C2=A0(an=
d a=C2=A0 Securities and Exchange Commission inquiry). A culture of sexual =
harassment at a public company is pretty much a core form of securities fra=
ud these days.One point that I often make is that it is strange =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0not wrong necessarily, but certainly strange =E2=80=94=C2=A0to concei=
ve of the shareholders as victims of Activision=E2=80=99s alleged culture o=
f sexual harassment. But here it seems, still strange, but definitively tru=
e. Activision was worth $103.81 per share last February; now shareholders w=
ill get cashed out at $95, largely because the sexual-harassment allegation=
s drove down the price and created the opportunity for Microsoft to buy. In=
stead of selling at a premium, they will sell at a discount, because an und=
isclosed culture of sexual harassment sunk Activision=E2=80=99s prospects t=
o remain an independent public company. I guess they should sue!
