adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Web3 economics</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a trade.</p><ol style=
=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You start a business. Let=E2=80=99s say it=E2=
=80=99s a platform business, where you connect buyers and sellers of someth=
ing.[1] You connect people who want to rent out their cars or their houses =
and people who want to use them, or you run an exchange to connect buyers a=
nd sellers of stock or art or Beanie Babies.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">Your platform charges a fee. Say you charge 2% of the valu=
e of each transaction for yourself.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">You start doing some transactions with yourself. You list your hous=
e on the platform and then rent it from yourself, you sell some Beanie Babi=
es to yourself, whatever. You set up different accounts under different nam=
es (or enlist your friends) to conceal this. You charge yourself a fee; you=
 do $1,000 worth of transactions and pay yourself $20. Your net cost here i=
s pretty much zero, since you=E2=80=99re just sending money to yourself, th=
ough there may be some frictional costs.[2]</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">The next month, you do it again, but more so. You do $2,000 of tr=
ansactions with yourself and pay yourself $40.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">The next month, you go to a venture capitalist. =E2=80=9CLook =
at this business,=E2=80=9D you say. =E2=80=9CWe are doing gross transaction=
s of $2,000 a month, our revenue is $40 a month, we are already profitable =
and we=E2=80=99re growing at 100% per month.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</li>=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The venture capitalist is like =E2=80=9Cooh this =
business looks amazing, I=C2=A0love a fast-growing platform business, I wil=
l invest at 20x revenue.=E2=80=9D By =E2=80=9Crevenue=E2=80=9D she means $4=
80 a year (your current annualized run rate) so she values your business at=
 $9,600. She buys 10% of your company for $960.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">You stop trading with yourself, the platform=E2=80=99s revenu=
e goes to zero, the venture capitalist is out $960 and you keep the money. =
A year later you run this trade again with a different business and a diffe=
rent, or the same, venture capitalist. =E2=80=9CI have learned so much from=
 my failed startup,=E2=80=9D you tell VCs.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">Or! Even better! You put out a press release saying =E2=80=9CPromi=
nent Venture Capitalist Invests In Awesome Fast-Growing Platform,=E2=80=9D =
you get a lot of attention, and people start trading on your platform for r=
eal. You start to get real revenue, you become a real business, you stop tr=
ading with yourself, revenue keeps going up, and you and the venture capita=
list both become rich.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The main point=
 of this trade is that, in a frothy market for fast-growing companies, you =
can sell $1 of the right kind of revenue for much more than $1, and so it i=
s worth your while to=C2=A0<em>create=C2=A0</em>some revenue, dress it up t=
o=C2=A0look like the right kind of revenue and then sell it to someone.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But another=C2=A0point of this trade (the one =
in Step=C2=A08) is that in network-effects businesses these things can be s=
elf-fulfilling, and a fake business can turn into a real one.[3] If someone=
 is looking to rent a house in an app, she=E2=80=99s going to go to the app=
 she=E2=80=99s heard of; if yours is getting a lot of press for growing qui=
ckly and raising lots of money, she=E2=80=99ll go to your app.=C2=A0</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This trade, as I described it, is basically fraud=
,[4] and sometimes people do it and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/26417155.266630/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlua=
W9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMTEtMTkvcGF5aW5nLWZvci1wb3B1bGFyaXR5LWNhbi1iZS1mcmF1=
ZD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTE5MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U=
9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjAxMTkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB0195b79c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> get in trouble for it</a>. But there =
are subtler and far more interesting versions of the trade. Here is a very =
important one; let=E2=80=99s call it the =E2=80=9CWeb2 version=E2=80=9D:</p=
><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;=
">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You start a platform business.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You charge a fee of $2 per transaction=
.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You go to venture capitalists an=
d raise some money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You use the mo=
ney to pay people, say, $3 per transaction to use your service. You pay the=
m $3 per transaction and they pay you back $2 in fees. They keep $1. Free m=
oney!</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You get a lot of users, beca=
use everyone wants to use a service that pays them to use it.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Now you have the good things: Lots of (real) us=
ers, lots of revenue, fast growth.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>You do have one bad thing, which is that you lose money on every transacti=
on.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">That=E2=80=99s fine! =E2=80=9C=
Customer acquisition costs are high right now,=E2=80=9D you (and your inves=
tors!) say, =E2=80=9Cbut they will come down as the platform matures and ac=
hieves scale.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You go to s=
ome more venture capitalists and raise a=C2=A0<em>ton=C2=A0</em>of money on=
 that premise. Or you go public on that premise.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">You stop paying people to use the service.</li>=09<li =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Maybe Step 8 was right! Maybe by this time yo=
ur users=C2=A0are so dependent on the service, and the service is so good, =
and the network effects are so powerful, that they keep using it once you s=
tart charging them to use it instead of paying them to use it. And then you=
r service is a huge success and you=E2=80=99re a billionaire.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Or maybe it was wrong, the service dies, the ve=
nture capitalists lose their investment and you get to keep whatever cash y=
ou took out and do this again in a year as a battle-hardened=C2=A0repeat fo=
under.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Web2 version of the trade =
is central to the story of the last decade in the U.S. tech industry. We so=
metimes called it the =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/26417155.266630/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDUtMTgvc2lsaWNvbi12YWxsZXktcy1zdWJzY3JpcHRpb24tZnJlZS1mb=
3ItYWxsP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMTkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3Nv=
dXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDExOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB36bda10c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">MoviePass economy</a>,=E2=80=9D =
the idea that venture capitalists would subsidize consumers=E2=80=99 lifest=
yles because they valued customer growth=C2=A0above everything else (includ=
ing profitability). Or there=E2=80=99s the term =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26417155.266630/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDEtMzEvZG9uLXQtYmxpdHpzY2FsZS1=
hZ2FpbnN0LXlvdXJzZWxmP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMTkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW=
1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDExOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249b=
W9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3dd1597a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">blitzscaling</a>,=
=E2=80=9D the idea that by throwing enormous quantities of money at a compa=
ny in a network-effects business you can make it the dominant player and th=
en pivot to profitability.=C2=A0There is no single outcome to these stories=
, no simple lesson to take from them. Sometimes it=E2=80=99s the outcome in=
 Step 11 above: User acquisition costs decline with scale and network effec=
ts, you jack up the price, and the unprofitable fast-growing subsidized ser=
vice becomes profitable. Other times it=E2=80=99s the outcome in Step 12. M=
oviePass <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26417155.=
266630/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDgt=
MDcvbW92aWVwYXNzLXdvcmtlZC1vdXQtZ3JlYXQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDExOTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkY=
mdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMTE5Jn=
V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB54f44d73" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 went hilariously bankrupt</a>.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One w=
ay to characterize the Web2 version is that instead of=C2=A0<em>trading wit=
h yourself</em>, you=C2=A0<em>got your investors to trade with you</em>. Yo=
u generated volume on your platform=C2=A0<em>from your investors</em>, indi=
rectly, by taking their money (the investment in Step 3) and turning it int=
o revenue (the customer subsidy in Step 4). A dollar of investment=C2=A0cap=
ital can be turned into revenue, and then sold to new investors at a multip=
le of that revenue. This is arguably=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>for your (earl=
y) investors. They=C2=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>a higher valuation. They are hap=
py for you to turn their money into revenue. They hope that you will turn i=
t into long-term stable recurring revenue (Step 11). But if you just turn i=
t into fake revenue, then maybe they can still sell their shares to the nex=
t sucker before it collapses.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We talked las=
t month about the economics of Web3, the popular current term for crypto pl=
atform businesses. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/26417155.266630/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLz=
IwMjEtMTItMjEvdGhlcmUtcy1pbnNpZGUtaW5mb3JtYXRpb24taW4tc2VjLWZpbGluZ3M_Y21wa=
WQ9QkJEMDExOTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3Ns=
ZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMTE5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cB0686d8df" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> I wrote</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">A basic premise of Web3 is that every product is simultaneousl=
y an investment opportunity. If you sign up for a Web3 social network or ch=
at room or trading venue or let=E2=80=99s-buy-the-Constitution lark, you wi=
ll get some of that project=E2=80=99s tokens, which will entitle you to use=
 the project=E2=80=99s app or exchange or Constitution, and which will give=
 you some notional say in the decentralized governance of the project. Also=
 the tokens will appreciate in value if the project takes off and more peop=
le want to use it. It=E2=80=99s as if being an early user of Facebook or Ub=
er also automatically made you a shareholder of Facebook or Uber, and when =
those services got huge you got rich.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">The move is to combine (1) Web3 economics (every product is an inve=
stment) with (2) the basic=C2=A0trade I have sketched out here (turn invest=
ment capital into revenue). Here is how that move might work:</p><ol style=
=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You start a platform business on Web3, crypto,=
 blockchains, etc. It has a =E2=80=9Cgovernance token,=E2=80=9D which is a =
little bit like a share of stock but you get to say it=E2=80=99s not a secu=
rity.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You charge a fee of 2% for p=
eople who use the platform. Holders of the governance token might have some=
 undefined, it=E2=80=99s-definitely-not-a-security future economic right to=
 those fees.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You give people=
 governance tokens for using your platform. These are rewards to incentiviz=
e early adopters, and they decline over time on an explicit schedule: Peopl=
e who use the platform a lot on the first week get a lot of governance toke=
ns, people who use it a lot the second week get fewer, people who use it in=
 the sixth month get even fewer, etc.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">There is an exchange of money for tokens, but indirectly. People use yo=
ur platform, they pay you (in dollars, Ether, etc.) to use the platform, an=
d you pay them (in governance tokens) for using the platform. Also, though,=
 they get to do whatever it is they do on the platform. In theory this coul=
d be renting out houses or cars or whatever, though in practice most crypto=
 platform businesses are about trading crypto. Let=E2=80=99s say your busin=
ess is an exchange for trading non-fungible tokens. People trade NFTs on yo=
ur platform, they pay you a fee for each trade, and (early on) you give the=
m governance tokens for each trade.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">So each early user of the platform is also an investor, and the more they=
 use it the more they are investing.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">They can sell the governance tokens freely because all of this stuff is =
effectively unregulated.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">How much =
are the governance tokens worth? It is hard to say, but they are sort of li=
ke shares of stock. Their value is some increasing function of the expected=
 future fee revenues of your platform, plus they have some intangible meme-=
y value based on how much hype your platform is getting.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The more trading there is on your platform, the mo=
re fees you collect and the more successful your business looks, and the mo=
re your governance token is worth, both because its expected cash flows are=
 higher and because it gets more hype and attention.</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">So people rush to your platform to trade as much as poss=
ible, which pumps up the value of the governance token, and they cheerfully=
 pay=C2=A0you the 2% fee to get governance tokens that they can sell at an =
immediate profit.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">These people do =
not necessarily want the NFTs that are being sold on your platform, so=C2=
=A0<em>they=C2=A0</em>trade with themselves. They set up two crypto wallets=
 and sell NFTs from one to the other, creating fake volume, =E2=80=9Cwash t=
rades.=E2=80=9D The trades aren=E2=80=99t real, the trades are just (1) an =
excuse to pay you a 2% fee on a large notional in exchange for a lot of val=
uable governance tokens and (2) a way to make your platform look popular so=
 that the governance tokens become valuable and they can sell them at a pro=
fit.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">And people buy the governance=
 tokens because (1) your platform is popular, (2) it is growing fast,=C2=A0=
(3) it is making money, and (4) it is getting a lot of hype =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
exactly the reasons a venture capitalist would have invested in your platfo=
rm in the Web2 version.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Eventually=
 you stop handing out so many governance tokens=C2=A0(the rewards decline o=
n a set schedule, see Step 3), and people stop doing huge wash trades with =
themselves to build hype and collect governance tokens.</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">Maybe then your thing collapses, the early wash trade=
rs made a fortune, and the people who bought their governance tokens are ho=
lding the bag.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Or maybe not! Maybe=
 all the fake trading created enough hype for your platform to attract real=
 trading, and your platform becomes good and people keep using it even afte=
r you stop paying them to use it.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The=
 Web3 version effectively combines the user incentives and the venture capi=
talist incentives from the Web2 version. Whereas the Web2 version of this t=
rade=C2=A0<em>indirectly=C2=A0</em>takes money from venture capitalists and=
 turns it into revenue, so that you can sell more shares to venture capital=
ists at a high multiple of revenue, the Web3 version=C2=A0<em>directly=C2=
=A0</em>takes money from user-investors and turns it into revenue, so that =
you (and they) can sell more governance tokens to more user-investors at an=
 even higher Web3-hype-driven multiple of revenue.=C2=A0<em>Web3 has refine=
d and perfected this trade,</em>=C2=A0in a way that makes it just about pla=
usibly sustainable.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThis is, essen=
tially, a pyramid scheme,=E2=80=9D said Dror Poleg in an <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26417155.266630/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZHJv=
