estors and creators of nonfungible tokens -- a market that has ballooned to=
 $44 billion, Chainalysis data show, and attracted fans from Justin Bieber =
to Melania Trump -- face billions of dollars in taxes and rates as high as =
37%, according to tax experts. Internal Revenue Service officials who deal =
with tax evaders say they are gearing up for a crackdown.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The surprises looming for NFT enthusiasts when tax fil=
ing season begins this month are crypto=E2=80=99s latest wake-up call from =
Washington as officials across the U.S. government set their sights on the =
burgeoning industry. The rules about taxing tokens aren=E2=80=99t clear, le=
aving NFT collectors scrambling to calculate how much they owe. Investors m=
ay not realize they need to pay any taxes at all or that they should file m=
ore than once a year, increasing the odds they=E2=80=99ll face future penal=
ties.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By like 2040 the entire =
U.S. government will be funded by taxing NFT wash traders.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Incidentally! There are a lot of people in the world and al=
most all of them would prefer to pay lower taxes rather than higher taxes. =
But there is a small category of people who are intensely interested in pay=
ing higher taxes. There are people who will walk into a casino with a sack =
of cash, buy $1 million of chips at a table, carry them directly to a cashi=
er, cash the chips out for $1 million, declare $1 million of gambling incom=
e to the IRS and pay taxes on it.[5]=C2=A0Of course they don=E2=80=99t have=
 $1 million of gambling income in this scenario: They walked in with $1 mil=
lion and walked out with $1 million, their gambling income is zero.=C2=A0Wh=
y call it gambling income? Because once you declare $1 million of gambling =
income and pay taxes on it, you can use what=E2=80=99s left over=C2=A0to bu=
y houses and cars and college tuition and stuff. Whereas=C2=A0<em>before=C2=
=A0</em>they declared it as gambling income, when it was just cash in a sac=
k, it was =E2=80=A6=C2=A0probably it was the proceeds of selling illegal dr=
ugs, though there are other ways to end up with $1 million of questionable =
cash in a sack. If you buy a house with=C2=A0cash in a sack it is going to =
raise questions.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is called =E2=80=9Cmo=
ney laundering,=E2=80=9D and the essential component of money laundering is=
=C2=A0<em>generating fake taxable income</em>. If you take $13,800 out of=
=C2=A0your (legitimate, previously taxed) bank account, and you use it to b=
uy cryptocurrency in a wallet that you tell your accountant and the IRS abo=
ut, and you then use that cryptocurrency to buy a Meebit, and then you take=
 $50 million out of your sack of illegal money, and you use it to buy crypt=
ocurrency in a wallet that you=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>tell your a=
ccountant about, and then you use=C2=A0<em>that </em>cryptocurrency to buy =
the Meebit from your declared wallet, and then you take the $50 million of=
=C2=A0cryptocurrency out of the declared wallet and put it back in your (le=
gitimate) bank account, and then you write the IRS a check for $20 million =
saying =E2=80=9Cah I=E2=80=99ve been selling NFTs, what fun I have had, but=
 I have to pay the IRS my fair share,=E2=80=9D then =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I am obv=
iously not going to give you advice on crime but it=E2=80=99s possible you=
=E2=80=99ve got something there?=C2=A0Like, nobody has any idea what a Meeb=
it is worth, so this string of outlandish numbers is somewhat plausible? It=
