id</a> in a letter to public-company chief executives this week, =E2=80=9Ci=
t is a privilege.=E2=80=9D Tiger Global does not go around saying rude stuf=
f like that!</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That anecdote is from <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26417155.266630/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMi8wMS8xOS90ZWNobm9sb2d5L3RlY2gtc3RhcnR1cC1mdW5k=
aW5nLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9f05cbb0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Erin Griffith=E2=80=
=99s New York Times story</a> about how crazy startup financing is right no=
w:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s so crazy that m=
ore than 900 tech start-ups are each worth more than $1 billion. In 2015, 8=
0 seemed like a lot.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s so crazy =
that hot start-ups no longer have to pitch investors for money. The investo=
rs are the ones pitching them.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s=
 so crazy that founders can start raising money on a Friday afternoon and h=
ave a deal closed by Sunday night.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">You can tell this as a story of irrational exuberance, too much money =
floating around etc., or you can tell it as a story of=C2=A0<em>rational=C2=
=A0</em>exuberance, too much change happening too quickly:</p><blockquote><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors and founders have adopted a seize-the=
-day mentality, believing the pandemic created a once-in-a-lifetime opportu=
nity to shake things up. Phil Libin, an entrepreneur and investor, said the=
 pandemic had changed every aspect of society so much that start-ups were a=
ccomplishing five years of progress in one year.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">=E2=80=9CThe basic fabric of the world is up for grabs,=E2=80=9D he s=
aid, calling this time =E2=80=9Cthe changiest the world has ever been.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He makes videocon=
ferencing software. I suppose the point is that in 2022 there are relativel=
y few people =E2=80=94=C2=A0more than there have been in the past, let=E2=
=80=99s stipulate, but still not that many =E2=80=94=C2=A0who are realistic=
ally able to change the basic fabric of the world, and relatively many peop=
le =E2=80=94=C2=A0surely more than there have ever been in the past =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0who can write them nine-figure checks after a weekend of due dilig=
ence. The power dynamic is lopsided, which shows up in lots of ways: billio=
n-dollar valuations everywhere, investors pleading to get into deals, found=
er-friendly governance terms, some amount of tolerance for fraud, etc.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile in public markets there is a lot of e=
xuberance, sure, but there's a bit less of <em>this</em>. Public investors =
really don=E2=80=99t have to court companies much, and in fact going public=
, even now, requires a company to put together a prospectus and a pitch dec=
k and go out and market <em>itself</em> to investors, an uncomfortable reve=
rsal. Due diligence is tougher, and tolerance for fraud is lower, just in t=
he sense that public companies are required to make timely public disclosur=
es of material facts and publish audited financial statements and generally=
 give investors more information than =E2=80=9Chere=E2=80=99s where to send=
 the check.=E2=80=9D But if you stay private, the unsolicited checks keep a=
rriving every day. Why bother trying to go public?</p><table class=3D"heade=
